Part 1 : Additional processes

Exercise 2 : Explosive process

1. Simulate an explosive ARMA(p,q) process. You are free to select numbers for p and q.

set.seed(123)
#Generating a Gaussian white noises process : 
wn <- rnorm(1000,0,1)
#Generating the ARMA(p,q) process : 
#Un processus explosif est un processus possdant au moins une racine autoregressive hors du cercle unit
arma_process <- wn[1:2]
for (t in 3:1000){
  arma_process[t] = 1.2*arma_process[t-1] + wn[t] + 0.8*wn[t-1]
}

# Reprsentation graphique du rsultat : 
df <- data.frame(x = 1:1000, y = arma_process)
arma_plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x = df$x, y = df$y, col = "Processus ARMA(1,1)\nExplosif gnr")) + geom_line() + ggtitle("Processus ARMA(1,1) explosif") + xlab("Index (1~1000)") + ylab("Arma_process")
arma_plot
On observe dj graphiquement un premier rsultat pour la question 2 tant labscence de stationnarit due la divergence partir dun certain rang. Cette explosion est due au fait que la racine du polynome de la partie AR du processus est situe lintrieur du cercle unitaire (On le verifiera par la suite).

2. Verify your ARMA(p,q) process does not respect the required conditions to be stationary. Use all the tools you know to reply to this question.

autocovariance_arma <- acf(arma_process, lag = 20, type = "covariance")

autocorrelation_arma <- acf(arma_process, lag = 20, type = "correlation")

pacf_arma <- pacf(arma_process, lag = 20)
#Circle <- arima(arma_process, order = c(1,0,1))
#plot(Circle)
Un message derreur est renvoy. Ce dernier provient du fait que la racine (1/1.2) du polynme caractristique de la partie AR du processus arma est situe linterieur du cercle unitaire, au del de ce que le plot peut reprsenter. Nanmoins, cela vient tout de mme confirmer labscence de stationnarit du processus.

On peut nanmoins procder autrement pour reprsenter le cercle unitaire et les racines du polynme caractristique AR :

coeff_AR <- c(1,-1.2) # Coefficients du polynme caractristique AR
coeff_MA <- c(1,0.8) # Coefficients du polynme caractristique MA
AR_roots <- polyroot(coeff_AR)
MA_roots <- polyroot(coeff_MA)

AR_roots <- matrix(c(AR_roots)) 
MA_roots <- matrix(c(MA_roots))

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(
  AR_roots,
  ylim=c(-1, 1),
  col = "red",
  asp=1,
  main="Racines AR",
  panel.first=c(
    lines(complex(modulus=1, argument=0.01*2*pi)^(0:100), col='blue'),
    abline(h=0, col='black'),
    abline(v=0, col='black')
  )
)

plot(
  MA_roots,
  ylim=c(-1, 1),
  col = "red",
  asp=1,
  main="Racines AR",
  panel.first=c(
    lines(complex(modulus=1, argument=0.01*2*pi)^(0:100), col='blue'),
    abline(h=0, col='black'),
    abline(v=0, col='black')
  )
)
Comme prvu, la racine du polynme caractristique AR est situe linterieur du cercle unitaire. Ainsi, il ya abscence de stationnarit.

We continue the study of ARMA models using the US Producer Price Index (excluding fresh food and energy). The data are available since 1974 until now. Can the ARMA framework help us to model the dynamics of this key variable and anticipate its behavior ?

PPI <- read.csv("usppi.csv" ,header = TRUE, sep = ",")

2. Calculate the monthly growth rate of the PPI between January 1981 and December 2021. Can the PPI inflation be modeled now with an ARMA(p,q) ?

Monthly_gr <- data.frame(Date = PPI$Date[85:576], MGR = 0*PPI$usppi[85:576])
for (i in 85:576){
  Monthly_gr$MGR[i-84] <- (PPI$usppi[i] - PPI$usppi[i-1])/PPI$usppi[i-1]
}

MGR_plot <- ggplot(Monthly_gr, aes(x = Monthly_gr$Date, y = Monthly_gr$MGR, col = "Monthly growth rate representation"))  + geom_line() + xlab("Date") + ylab("MGR") + ggtitle("Monthly Growth Rate of PPI\n(January 1981~December 2021)")
MGR_plot

4. Using the arima.sim function calculate the likelihood values for different combination p and q. Calculate then the values of the Akaike and the Bayesian information criteria for all the couple p and q. Which combination of p and q is qualified according to the Akaike and the Bayesian criteria ?

AR_order <- seq(0,4)
MA_order <- seq(0,4)


likelihood = matrix(0,nrow = max(AR_order),ncol = max(MA_order))
AIC = matrix(0,nrow = max(AR_order),ncol = max(MA_order))
BIC = matrix(0,nrow = max(AR_order),ncol = max(MA_order))

for (p in AR_order) {
  for (q in MA_order) {
    model = arima(Monthly_gr$MGR, order = c(p,0,q))
    likelihood[p,q] = model$loglik # On recup la log vraissemblance
    AIC[p,q] = model$aic # On recupre l'AIC
    BIC[p,q] = BIC(model) # On recupre le BIC
  }
}

8. Quality check : Explain the type of quality check we have to run to derive a robust conclusion regarding the estimated specification. Run the required quality checks seen during the class. Comment your results

On commence par effectuer un test de Ljung-Box pour tester la dpendance du modle :

Ljung_box <- Box.test(MGR, lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
Ljung_box
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  MGR
## X-squared = 714.14, df = 20, p-value < 2.2e-16
On constate que la p-value du test est infrieure 0.05 et mme 0.01. On peut alors affirmer avec un niveau de confiance de 99% que le modle est autocorrl.

Par la suite :

On considre la RMSE pour estimer lerrreur quadratique moyenne du modle pour tester la prcision de ce dernier.

RMSE <- function(observed,predicted)
{
  rmse <- sqrt(mean((observed-predicted)^2))
  rmse
}
Rmse <- RMSE(MGR,estimated_MGR) 
Rmse # 0.003019579
## [1] 0.003019579
On obtient une erreur quadratique moyenne de lordre de 10^-3, ce qui vient confirmer les hypothses effectues. Le modle est prcis comme on a pu lobserver sur le graphique de comparaison prcedemment.
